        <section class="prose mt-10">
          <h2>How Michigan city income tax works</h2>
          <p>Michigan allows certain cities to levy a local income tax in addition to the <strong>Michigan state income tax</strong>. If you live or work in one of these cities, your wages may be subject to city income tax that is typically withheld from your paycheck.</p>

          <h3>Who has to pay Michigan city income tax?</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Residents</strong> of a taxing city usually pay city income tax on all taxable income, regardless of where it is earned.</li>
            <li><strong>Nonresidents</strong> generally pay city income tax only on income earned while working or doing business in that city.</li>
            <li>Some cities also tax <strong>business income, rental income, and self‑employment income</strong> connected to the city.</li>
          </ul>

          <p>Each city publishes its own forms and instructions. See the Michigan Department of Treasury’s <a href="https://www.michigan.gov/taxes/citytax" target="_blank" rel="noopener">City Income Tax</a> page for official details and links to city websites.</p>

          <h3>Formula used by this calculator</h3>
          <div class="formula-box text-sm">
            <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Step 1 – City taxable income</p>
            <p>\[
\text{City taxable income} = \max\bigl(0,\ \text{Wages in city} - \text{Pre‑tax deductions}\bigr)
\]</p>
            <p class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1">Step 2 – City income tax</p>
            <p>\[
\text{City tax} = \text{City taxable income} \times \text{City tax rate}
\]</p>
            <p class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1">Step 3 – Take‑home pay after city tax</p>
            <p>\[
\text{Take‑home} = \text{Total income} - \text{City tax}
\]</p>
            <p class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1">Step 4 – Effective city tax rate</p>
            <p>\[
\text{Effective rate} = \frac{\text{City tax}}{\text{Total income}} \times 100\%
\]</p>
          </div>

          <p>This tool does <strong>not</strong> calculate credits for taxes paid to another city, nor does it handle every special deduction or exemption that may appear on a city return. It is intended as a quick paycheck‑level estimate.</p>

          <h3>Common Michigan city tax questions</h3>

          <h4>Do I pay city income tax if I live in one city and work in another?</h4>
          <p>It depends on the specific cities involved. Many Michigan cities tax residents on all income and nonresidents on income earned in the city. In some cases, you may owe tax to both your <strong>work city</strong> and your <strong>home city</strong>, with a credit to avoid double taxation. Check each city’s instructions carefully.</p>

          <h4>Is Michigan city income tax deductible?</h4>
          <p>For federal tax purposes, city income tax is generally treated as a <strong>state and local tax (SALT)</strong>. If you itemize deductions on your federal return, it may be included in the SALT deduction, subject to the federal cap. For Michigan state income tax, city income tax is usually <strong>not</strong> deductible. Always confirm with a tax professional.</p>

          <h4>Where can I find official Michigan city tax forms and rates?</h4>
          <ul>
            <li><a href="https://www.michigan.gov/taxes/citytax" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Michigan Department of Treasury – City Income Tax</a></li>
            <li>Individual city websites (e.g., Detroit, Grand Rapids, East Lansing, Flint, etc.)</li>
            <li>Michigan’s list of <a href="https://www.michigan.gov/taxes/questions/iit/accordion/general/what-cities-impose-an-income-tax" target="_blank" rel="noopener">cities that impose an income tax</a></li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Limitations and disclaimers</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>This calculator is for <strong>educational and planning purposes only</strong>.</li>
            <li>Rates and rules can change; always verify with the city or a qualified tax advisor.</li>
            <li>The tool does not prepare or file your tax return and does not provide legal or tax advice.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

